WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.030
[Music]

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:11.310
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. Today&nbsp;
we're going to carry on talking about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.310 --> 00:00:18.630
patterns in algebra. Our aim is to move towards&nbsp;
setting up proper foundations for algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:18.630 --> 00:00:26.130
which means defining rather carefully and clearly&nbsp;
what the main objects of interest are. So far,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:26.130 --> 00:00:30.330
we've been exploring a number of different&nbsp;
realms within algebra, within baby algebra,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:30.330 --> 00:00:35.760
different aspects of the way polynomials&nbsp;
appear. We're going to continue with that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:35.760 --> 00:00:41.790
today and talk about different ways of approaching&nbsp;
sequences and patterns that naturally appear.

00:00:41.790 --> 00:00:47.970
Last time, we talked about the table of&nbsp;
differences formed by the triangular numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:47.970 --> 00:00:52.530
and I'm going to adjust my notation a&nbsp;
little bit now to make it a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.530 --> 00:00:58.980
more methodical. Instead of having the difference&nbsp;
2 between 1 and 3 directly above both of them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:58.980 --> 00:01:04.890
I'm going to move over a little bit to the&nbsp;
right so that now 1 plus 2 equals 3. So again,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:04.890 --> 00:01:08.670
this thing here represents the&nbsp;
difference between the 6 and the 10.

00:01:08.670 --> 00:01:17.250
Here's our sequence of triangular numbers whose&nbsp;
nth term is n times (n + 1) over 2. There,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.250 --> 00:01:22.410
the differences are, of course, just the&nbsp;
natural numbers themselves. The differences&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:22.410 --> 00:01:28.890
between them are all 1, and the differences&nbsp;
between all the ones are all zeros. But when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:28.890 --> 00:01:33.030
we go up in this pattern, things become&nbsp;
simpler. When we go down in the pattern,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:33.030 --> 00:01:37.200
they become a little bit more complicated.&nbsp;
So for example, if we start with 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:43.470
then this would have to be 4 so that 1 plus&nbsp;
3 is 4. So we had a new sequence of numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:43.470 --> 00:01:50.760
which might be called the tetrahedral numbers. In&nbsp;
this sequence, the 20 represents the sum 1 plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:57.120
3 plus 6 plus 10. So each one of these numbers&nbsp;
is the sum of the first n triangular numbers.

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:04.920
Here's the geometrical interpretation of the&nbsp;
tetrahedral numbers. Something like 20 can be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:04.920 --> 00:02:10.560
thought of in terms of a three-dimensional stack&nbsp;
of triangular numbers. There's one, there's three,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:16.310
there's six, there's ten. They're sort of stacked&nbsp;
up on top of each other to form a tetrahedron.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:16.310 --> 00:02:22.790
This has a physical interpretation in terms of&nbsp;
a stack of cannonballs. So if you imagine this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:22.790 --> 00:02:29.270
bottom layer representing ten cannonballs,&nbsp;
the green ones here arranged in a triangle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:29.270 --> 00:02:37.250
then on top of those ten cannonballs we can&nbsp;
stack six more in the indents formed by three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:37.250 --> 00:02:43.700
bottom-layer ones. So there are six on top&nbsp;
of them, and then we could furthermore stack&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:43.700 --> 00:02:50.240
another three on top of those, and then one on the&nbsp;
top, giving us a nice little tetrahedral pyramid.

00:02:50.990 --> 00:02:58.070
Alright, so that's a physical meaning to these&nbsp;
tetrahedral numbers, and it turns out that their&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.070 --> 00:03:05.150
formula is given by this polynomial expression:&nbsp;
n times (n + 1) times (n + 2) divided by 6.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:05.150 --> 00:03:11.120
You might like to check that, and even better,&nbsp;
you might like to try to prove that that's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:11.120 --> 00:03:17.930
formula. I'll tell you later on how to do that in&nbsp;
a more systematic way. Of course, we can continue.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.930 --> 00:03:25.640
We could then ask, well, what are the sums of the&nbsp;
tetrahedral numbers? In keeping with this picture,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:31.520
you might think that these numbers represent some&nbsp;
kind of four-dimensional stack of cannonballs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:31.520 --> 00:03:37.250
and one can, in fact, make that precise. So&nbsp;
as we carry on down in this pattern, we are in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:37.250 --> 00:03:45.140
fact investigating higher-dimensional analogs&nbsp;
of tetrahedrons or triangles. It's a rather&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:45.140 --> 00:03:50.540
interesting pattern, and it all comes about&nbsp;
essentially built up from the natural numbers.

00:03:50.540 --> 00:03:57.710
So here are those square numbers: 1, 4, 9, 16,&nbsp;
with a table of differences that they generate.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:57.710 --> 00:04:03.380
The differences between the square numbers are&nbsp;
the successive odd numbers, and the differences&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.380 --> 00:04:11.960
between the odd numbers are always 2, and the&nbsp;
differences between the twos are 0. If we go down,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:17.150
it becomes a little bit more complicated and&nbsp;
creates a new sequence so that this is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:17.150 --> 00:04:21.770
differences in this new sequence. Well, that would&nbsp;
mean that 1 plus 4 would have to be equal to 5,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.770 --> 00:04:27.480
5 plus 9 would be 14, 14 plus 16 equals 30,&nbsp;
and so on. So it's easy to generate this once&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:34.230
you've generated the line above it. The square&nbsp;
numbers, of course, have the formula n squared,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:34.230 --> 00:04:41.100
and we saw last time, or I stated last time,&nbsp;
that the sum of the first n squares has this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:46.200
particular polynomial formula: n times&nbsp;
(n + 1) times (2n + 1) divided by 6.

00:04:48.660 --> 00:04:53.400
These numbers also have a nice geometrical&nbsp;
interpretation also in terms of a stack of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:53.400 --> 00:05:00.180
cannonballs, but this time a rather more wobbly&nbsp;
stack. A stack where you decide to arrange the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.180 --> 00:05:06.870
bottom layer in a square—maybe you have a square&nbsp;
box to fit the cannonballs in. Now we have four&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:06.870 --> 00:05:14.490
this way by four this way, so 16 on the bottom&nbsp;
layer represented by these 16 dots here. Then in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.490 --> 00:05:20.250
the indents formed by them, nine in the layer&nbsp;
above them represented by this little square,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:20.250 --> 00:05:28.770
and then above them you could fit four more in,&nbsp;
and one up at the very top. The whole number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:28.770 --> 00:05:35.100
in this particular pyramidal array would&nbsp;
be 1 plus 4 plus 9 plus 16, which is 30.

00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:43.260
It's not at all so obvious how to define&nbsp;
pentagonal numbers, especially since fitting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:43.260 --> 00:05:49.230
cannonballs around layers of five doesn't work&nbsp;
very well, but here's one natural approach that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:49.230 --> 00:05:54.510
been studied for a long time. We start with a&nbsp;
pentagon with one cannonball right in the middle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.510 --> 00:06:01.980
and then we enlarge that picture—so we'll put that&nbsp;
one right there—by adding another layer, making&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.980 --> 00:06:08.670
a bigger pentagon around the original one. Then&nbsp;
there are three more sides with two on each side,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:08.670 --> 00:06:15.150
so we're adding four to get a total of five. Then&nbsp;
in the next step, we copy this picture over here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.150 --> 00:06:20.700
and then we add another layer, or as maybe&nbsp;
the ancient Greeks would call such a thing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:20.700 --> 00:06:29.520
an "omen," another layer of cannonballs, this time&nbsp;
three on each side of three sides, getting a total&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:29.520 --> 00:06:36.030
of twelve. We can continue this; at each stage,&nbsp;
we add another layer. Now this layer has four,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:36.030 --> 00:06:43.180
four, four in each of the three rows that we're&nbsp;
adding to the original. In this way, we get a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:43.180 --> 00:06:49.510
sequence of numbers which we might call pentagonal&nbsp;
numbers: 1, 5, 12, 22, and it's a nice exercise&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:49.510 --> 00:06:59.590
to try to convince yourself that the formula for&nbsp;
P_n is this thing here: n times (3n - 1) over 2.

00:06:59.590 --> 00:07:04.780
Let's have a look at the table of differences&nbsp;
that this sequence generates. Here are our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:04.780 --> 00:07:10.630
pentagonal numbers, and here are the differences&nbsp;
between the pentagonal numbers, starting with 4,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:10.630 --> 00:07:17.680
then 7, then 10, then 13. We see that there's&nbsp;
a pattern between the differences which is made&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.680 --> 00:07:20.920
clear if we go up and talk about the&nbsp;
differences between the differences:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:20.920 --> 00:07:27.250
then it is simply all threes. So now it's clear&nbsp;
how to extend this table. We could carry on this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:27.250 --> 00:07:31.990
way without actually drawing pictures, just by&nbsp;
extending the table of differences. This would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.990 --> 00:07:39.430
allow us to carry on. We can also extend, as&nbsp;
we did before, to higher-dimensional analogs.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:39.430 --> 00:07:43.360
In this case, it's not so clear what it means.&nbsp;
So we can start with a 1 here and then create&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:43.360 --> 00:07:50.200
a new line whose line of differences is this&nbsp;
one. So 1 + 5 is 6, 6 + 12 is 18, and so on.

00:07:50.200 --> 00:07:56.800
Does it make sense to extend this&nbsp;
table to the left? Well, if we do,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:56.800 --> 00:08:01.540
there's only really one reasonable way of doing it&nbsp;
because this pattern of threes obviously wants to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:01.540 --> 00:08:08.740
continue. So we have to continue this pattern of&nbsp;
threes. Well, if this is a three and that's four,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.740 --> 00:08:12.580
that we know, then this has got to be one&nbsp;
because this plus this has got to be this.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:14.200 --> 00:08:18.880
Then this has to be minus 2 because this&nbsp;
plus three has to equal one—that's forced.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:23.620
And then that's forced, and that's forced.&nbsp;
Now we're getting going down by three here.

00:08:23.620 --> 00:08:28.840
Now what happens to the pentagonal numbers&nbsp;
themselves when we extend them? Here there's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:28.840 --> 00:08:34.990
one, here there's one, there must be a zero here,&nbsp;
and two plus minus two is zero. That's got to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:34.990 --> 00:08:39.901
two, that's got to be seven in order for seven&nbsp;
plus minus five to equal two. That's got to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:39.901 --> 00:08:47.650
fifteen, that's got to be twenty-six, and now it&nbsp;
seems as if we're getting another second series&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:47.650 --> 00:08:57.040
of pentagonal numbers which are not, at least at&nbsp;
first, recognizable in a geometrical form. So the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:57.040 --> 00:09:04.660
question is, are these numbers 2, 7, 15, 26 also&nbsp;
pentagonal numbers? And if so, what do they mean?

00:09:04.660 --> 00:09:11.680
It turns out there's a very interesting piece&nbsp;
of evidence for this. It's not just an armchair&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:11.680 --> 00:09:17.980
exercise; there's a piece of solid mathematical&nbsp;
evidence that comes to play, discovered by the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:17.980 --> 00:09:24.280
greatest mathematician of modern times, who is&nbsp;
Leonard Euler. He discovered that pentagonal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:24.280 --> 00:09:29.980
numbers are not just geometrical curiosities but&nbsp;
are intimately connected with some other things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:29.980 --> 00:09:35.350
in particular with number theory. I'm going&nbsp;
to tell you about that next time when I talk&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:35.350 --> 00:09:41.500
about Leonard Euler and how he essentially&nbsp;
resolved this question—a very interesting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:41.500 --> 00:09:46.630
development. I hope you'll join me for that.&nbsp;
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:09:46.630 --> 00:09:46.660
[Music]

